I hope everyone is healthy and safe!

The SCV Superintendents have been working with Stephanie English from Supervisor Barger's office to provide a question and answer forum with Dr. Ferrer, Director of Los Angeles County Department of Public Health, and Dr. Sharon Balter, Director of Acute Communicable Disease, and Dr. Robert Gilchick, Child and Adolescent Health Section Chief of our Division of Maternal, Child, & Adolescent Health. SCV Educator Community Forum will be on Monday July 13 at 6:00 pm. The public is invited to view the meeting on YouTube at https://youtu.be/5f5pY8tSDHg. The questions were submitted by employee groups from all five local SCV School Districts.

Thanks,

Steve Doyle
Superintendent
Castaic Union School District

post_text:
#DidYouKnow? The First People of Castaic (Kashtuk), which means "eyes" are the Tataviam (People Facing the Sun)? Their history is traced back to 450 A.D. Following the "mission period", many Tataviam returned to their ancestral lands and villages in Castaic and throughout the Santa Clarita, Antelope, San Fernando, and Simi Valleys, where they continue to live and thrive today! You may recognize the names of many other Tataviam villages: Piiru (Piru), Islay (Hasley), Cahuenga, Topanga, Tujunga, to name just a few.

For more information, please visit http://www.tataviam-nsn.us/

Good News Castaic Families!

Please see the update grab and go meals information below! We are so very fortunate to work with our super fantabulous SCV Food Services!

Beginning June 26, we will be offering Saturday and Sunday meals at the school sites. These meals (breakfast and lunch) will be sent home on Fridays except July 3, which will be sent home on July 2 for the entire three day weekend.

Other good news, we are adding breakfast to all the community sites including Old Town Newhall Library, Canyon Country JoAnne Darcy Library, and the Val Verde Community Center.

All meals are free to children 18 and younger.

Beginning June 26, we will be offering Saturday and Sunday meals at the school sites. These meals (breakfast and lunch) will be sent home on Fridays except July 3, which will be sent home on July 2 for the entire three day weekend. We are also adding breakfast to all the community sites including Old Town Newhall Library, Canyon Country JoAnne Darcy Library, and the Val Verde Community Center. All meals are free to children 18 and younger. School Day Cafe

post_text: This week we celebrate our classified employees who are critical to the success of our students. The bus drivers who get them to school safely and on time, the office staff and health clerks who attend to their daily needs, the instructional aides and library techs who support their learning experience to ensure that they are successful, the custodial and maintenance staff who keep our campuses beautiful, clean, and safe so that our students can thrive, our yard supervisors and yard duties who know every student by name, building crucial relationships and ensuring their safety everyday. Thank you for all that you do everyday to support our teachers and students! #TeamCUSD #CUSDProud

post_text:
#DidYouKnow? Governing Board Member, Stacy Dobbs, a CSUN Master of Social Work student, created a website as part of a mental health advocacy project aiming to provide support to parents and caregivers who are facing the challenges of COVID-19 and simultaneously working to manage anxiety and stress in children and themselves.

This project includes advocating to California legislators for support and funding for essential mental health services to ensure that mental health resources and services are available and accessible to all those who need extra support and emotional healing both during and after COVID-19.

Following is the link to Stacy's website, Keep Calm: Combating Anxiety During COVID-19, which provides tips for reducing stress, calming activities and mental health resources. #CUSDCares #HomeTogether

post_text: Bus pass registration for the 2020-2021 school year will be held from June 1 to June 30. Bus pass application forms will be available beginning June 1st online at https://buff.ly/2KYIbPP or from one of our school district lunch distribution sites. Due to the current school closures, the applications must be mailed to the Castaic Union School District office or submitted at one of our school district lunch distribution sites. The deadline for bus pass applications is June 30 and applications received after the deadline will be placed on a waitlist and transportation cannot be guaranteed at the start of the school year.

post_text:
We are so excited to begin another busy week with you. A few reminders:

1. It is helpful to stick to a routine or schedule everyday to ensure that your children stay current with school work and mentally sharp.

2. Enjoy some physical activity and join Mrs. Z for virtual PE on Mondays and Wednesdays. On alternate days, work in some walks, bike rides, or hikes.

3. Remember to take the kids out for a Grab n Go lunch everyday between 12-1pm at either LOS or NHE.

Please know that we care very much about you and your children (our families) and hope to make this experience as positive and stress-free as possible. Please let us know how we are doing and how we can best support you during this time at info@castaicusd.com. Wishing you well!

#MakeHopeHappenCUSD #CUSDCares #CUSDStrong #CUSDProud

March 15 at 8:43 PM ·

Dear Families,
If your child receives free or reduced lunch at school, please know that our District will be in contact with you. Currently the Castaic Union School District, along with the other school districts in the Santa Clarita Valley, are working with Food Services to create a safe plan to serve our students. We appreciate your patience. Information will be forthcoming. Thank you,
Vivian Fiss
Principal

Estimadas Familias,
Si su estudiante recibe almuerzo gratis o reducido en la escuela, queremos dejarle saber que nuestro Distrito se pondrá en contacto con usted pronto. Actualmente, nuestro Distrito, junto con los otros distritos escolares en el valle de Santa Clarita, están trabajando con los Servicios de Alimentos para realizar un plan para repartir comida a nuestros alumnos. Apreciamos su paciencia. Tendremos más información pronto.
Atentamente,
Vivian Fiss
Directora de la Escuela Northlake Hills

URGENT: CUSD School Closures

This message is to inform you that the Castaic Union School District – in concert with the other Santa Clarita School Districts - will be closing all schools starting Monday, March 16 and extending for a period of three weeks. On campus classes will resume after Spring Break Monday, April 13, 2020.

Please expect additional details in the next several hours.

post_text:
The public health crisis created by the coronavirus is not something any of us could reasonably have expected to happen, and we’re in uncharted waters as we work to prevent the spread of the illness. We have been following the guidance and direction of public health experts on how we can keep all who are part of our school community -- students, staff, family members and visitors -- safe in the midst of a growing health crisis. In collaboration with all SCV school districts, the City of Santa Clarita, SCV Sheriff's Department, and Los Angeles County Office of Education we are working to determine the best course of action at this time to ensure the health and safety of our students, staff, and community.

We ask for your patience and we will continue to do our best to keep you informed. Facts and circumstances may change quickly so we encourage you to check our website castaicusd.com regularly.

March 5 at 5:29 PM ·

This afternoon, representatives from the City, William S. Hart Union High School District, Newhall School District, Castaic Union School District, Henry Mayo Newhall Hospital, Santa Clarita Valley Sheriff's Station, The American Red Cross of Santa Clarita, SCV Senior Center, College of the Canyons, California Institute of the Arts, Senator Scott Wilk, Assemblywoman Christy Smith, Supervisor Kathryn Barger and others met to discuss each organization’s emergency preparedness plan for the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). Our organizations continue to collaborate with Los Angeles County to ensure we have the resources needed to respond as necessary and keep the public informed.

post_text: More pictures from Nikki and Bradley Bozeman's visit to #CastaicMiddleSchool. Bradley and Nikki Bozeman Foundation
shared_text:
Bradley and Nikki Bozeman Foundation is with Bảo Sơn Nguyễn Hữu and Nikki Hegstetter Bozeman.
February 28 at 4:13 PM ·

Stop 8: Castaic, CA - We are officially on the west coast and HALF way done with this journey! It’s crazy we feel like we have been traveling for months now but it has only been a couple short weeks. We have conquered so much and talked to so many students but have so much more left in us! We also thought it was fitting that we are halfway done with this journey on National Stand-Up To Bullying Day! During our stop in Castaic we were able to visit Castaic Middle School PAC. The students were so attentive and asked great questions. We also ate lunch at a local taco truck with one of the coolest principals we have been able to meet. In our 48 hours here we were also able to make it out to a local beach, drive pacific coast highway, stop at an amazing fruit stand, eat in-n-out burger, go to our first pottery class, and of course visit the happiest place on earth - DISNEYLAND! Also thank you to ESPN for sending an amazing photographer out to hang with us. We had a great time and got some really cool shots! Alright y’all - Next Stop: San Francisco, CA!!

post_text: Join us on March 4 at 6:00pm for a special, PARENTS ONLY screening of the movie “Screenagers, Next Chapter”. Filmmaker and physician Dr. Delaney Ruston takes the conversation around screens and teens to the next level with Screenagers NEXT CHAPTER: Uncovering Skills for Stress Resilience—a film that examines the science behind teen’s emotional challenges, the interplay of social media, and most importantly, what can be done in our schools and homes to help them build crucial skills to navigate stress, anxiety, and depression in our digital age. #LiveOakLeopards #CUSDCares Screenagers Movie

post_text: On Monday, #NorthlakeEagles students journeyed through the universe in a Sky Dome Planetarium. This was just one of the amazing events planned using a portion of the $40,000 raised by the students at their Color Run fundraiser last October. Students entered the dome and were introduced to a "star-filled" sky. They learned how to identify every planet in our solar system in dramatic "flights" towards each world, were introduced to Greek mythological characters in the stars, and witnesses the night sky in different seasons and from different global perspectives. #WOW

With one donation you may give a newborn, a child, a mother or father, a brother or sister another chance at life. In fact, you can help save up to three lives with one donation. Please join us and give blood and help us save lives. Castaic Middle School and the American Red Cross are hosting an upcoming blood drive. Please join our lifesaving mission and schedule an appointment today!

post_text: You may be hearing on the news that there is great concern regarding our children and the effects of SCREENTIME. Currently, 59% more teens are reporting depression symptoms than they did in 2011. Somewhere around 19% of girls ages 12 to 17 will experience a depressive episode in a given year and about 6% of boys. Please join us on February 26 for a FREE screening of SCREENAGERS. This film offers solutions on how we can help our kids navigate the digital world. Join us for Part 2, SCREENAGERS the Next Chapter, on March 4 to discover solutions for improved adolescent well-being in the digital age. https://buff.ly/2JLKm98 #CUSDCares #CUSDChangingLives #CUSDCommunity @SCREENAGERS

post_text: Congratulations to Carla Huffman on her recent retirement! Without a doubt, #TeamCUSD has been blessed with truly amazing teachers who genuinely care about our students, because "teaching is more like a ministry than a job". Teachers touch the lives of students in so many ways and for the past 18 years, Carla has encouraged, challenged and inspired students. Thank you Ryan Valencia, representing Assemblywoman Christy Smith and Stephanie English, representing Supervisor Kathryn Barger for celebrating Carla with us! @AsmChristySmith @KathrynBarger #CUSDProud #CUSDCares #CUSDChangingLives

post_text: Thank you #CUSDCommunity for your support this morning! You make us #CUSDProud!
shared_text:
Castaic Elementary School
January 25 at 5:08 PM ·

Today was our “Team Up to Clean Up” event at the Castaic Lake. We’d like to thank our wonderful CES PTA, and especially Jill Amanda Federman, for working so hard to make this event a huge success. Over 120 people from the community came out to pick up trash around the lake! What a great way to demonstrate kindness towards this special recreational area. We had support from Castaic Lake, Friends of Castaic Lake, Starbucks (on Castaic Rd.), Ralphs, and the crew from One Piece at a Time. Thank you! Thanks to everyone who came out to help! You truly made a difference! #CastaicElementaryPTA #CESCubs #onepieceatatime #beingkind

Last week our #NorthlakeEagles enjoyed an intricate, stylized fan dance in the finest tradition of the Korean court and a thrilling drum dance featuring unison drumming on suspended drums.

As part of the school's continuing efforts to enrich its curriculum and its students' educational experience, the school will present a special performance of Korean Classical Music & Dance Company. The performance was presented by The Music Center's education department which provides many offerings including live performances, classroom workshops, scholarship and training programs, online arts curriculum, on-campus events and professional development. #MakeHopeHappenCUSD #CUSDCares #CUSDChangingLives

post_text:
Dear Castaic Families,

We want to express our deepest condolences to the victims, their families and all those affected by today's tragic events at Saugus High School. We want to assure you that out of an abundance of caution and after consultation with Law Enforcement, we decided to place all of our campuses on lock down. We sincerely appreciate all of your cooperation and support during this challenging time. We know that you want to keep your children safe and that is our top priority as well.

All of our schools will be open tomorrow as regularly scheduled. We will have our school psychologists and counselors available for any students that need support. I have attached a document with some brief talking points and information for parents to assist in talking with your children about violence.

Warm regards,

Steve Doyle

Superintendent
text:
Dear Castaic Families,

We want to assure you that out of an abundance of caution and after consultation with Law Enforcement, we decided to place all of our campuses on lock down. We sincerely appreciate all of your cooperation and support during this challenging time. We know that you want to keep your children safe and that is our top priority as well.

All of our schools will be open tomorrow as regularly scheduled. We will have our school psychologists and counselors available for any students that need support. I have attached a document with some brief talking points and information for parents to assist in talking with your children about violence.

Steve Doyle

post_text:
VOLUNTEERS NEEDED
The Castaic Education Foundation is seeking volunteers to participate in the Junior Achievement program at your school. Founded in 1919, the purpose of Junior Achievement is to inspire and prepare young people to succeed in a global economy through activities focused on financial literacy, work readiness, and entrepreneurship. A big part of the program's success is the involvement of community and parent volunteers! Training and all materials are provided and the time commitment is only 1 hour a week for approximately 6 weeks. Several teachers at your school have signed up and volunteers are needed. Please contact Julia Phippen, Chairperson for the Castaic Ed. Foundation at 661-257-4500 x1566 or jphippen@castaicusd.com for more information. We plan to begin the program in January and hope to have all volunteers secured by winter break.
